{{Infobox artwork/wikidata|suppressfields=owner}}
'''''Portrait of Charlotte du Val d'Ognes''''' is an 1801 painting ([[portrait painting]]) by [[Marie-Denise Villers]]. It is in the collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref name=":1">{{cite web|title=Portrait of Charlotte du Val d'Ognes|publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/437903|accessdate=}}</ref> The painting was first acquired by the museum in 1922 and attributed to [[Jacques-Louis David|Jacques Louis David]]. Later, the painting was attributed to [[Constance Marie Charpentier]] and finally to Villers.

==Early history and creation==
Because the painting is unsigned, it has been attributed incorrectly over time.{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} It was first exhibited at the 1801 [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]], during the year that [[Jacques-Louis David|Jacques Louis David]] boycotted the exhibition.{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} A member of the Val d'Ognes family believed it had been painted by David.<ref name=":1" />

==Later history and display==
The Met bought the painting, attributed to David, for two hundred thousand dollars in 1922.{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} In 1951, [[Charles Sterling]] of the Met admitted that the painting may not have been David's.{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} Sterling was first tipped off that the painting was not David's because the artist had boycotted the 1801 Salon.<ref name=":1" /> The mistake was published in the Met's January 1951 ''Bulletin''.{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=56}}<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sterling|first=Charles|date=1951|title=A Fine "David" Reattributed|jstor=3257483|journal=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Bulletin|volume=9|issue=5|pages=121–132|doi=10.2307/3257483|registration=yes}}</ref> The painting may have been [[Constance Marie Charpentier|Constance Marie Charpentier's]] because of some evidence found in Salon entries seem to indicate it was hers, however David's name did not come off of the frame until 1977.{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} Sterling's reattribution of the painting to Charpentier was also based on analysis of her painting, ''Melancholy'' (1801).{{Sfn|Mainz|2001|p=247}}

Later, in 1996, Margaret Oppenheimer realized that the painting should instead be attributed to Marie Denise Villers.{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=56}}<ref name=":1" /> Oppenheimer's reattribution is based on a [[modello]] by Villers, ''A Young Woman Seated by a Window''.{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=57}}

The painting is currently on view at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in Gallery 613.<ref name=":1" />

==Description and interpretation==
The work depicts a [[woman]] drawing in front of a broken window. Behind the woman, a couple stand on a [[parapet]].{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} In the ''Concise Dictionary of Women Artists'' (2001), Valerie Mainz describes the broken window as a "''tour de force'' of the painter's art distinguishing, in its ''[[Trompe-l'œil|trompe-l'oeil]]'' effect, the view of the scene outside as to be seen as only partly through glass."{{Sfn|Mainz|2001|p=247}} The room depicted in the painting is actually a gallery of the [[Louvre]], as discovered by art historian, Ann Higonnet.{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=58}}{{Sfn|James|1997|p=xiii}}

Early description, when it was presumed to be David's assumed that the woman in the painting was his student, drawing him as he painted her.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=26 September 1938|title=Jacques Louis David (1748-1825)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f00EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA38&dq=%22charlotte%20du%20val%20d'ognes%22&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q=%22charlotte%20du%20val%20d'ognes%22&f=false|journal=LIFE|volume=5|issue=13|pages=38|via=}}</ref> [[André Maurois|Andre Maurois]] said that it was "a perfect picture, unforgettable."{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} Critical response to the work prior to attributing the work to Charpentier was often positive.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s6GSMUGGEmgC&lpg=PA23&dq=%22charlotte%20du%20val%20d'ognes%22&pg=PA23#v=onepage&q=%22charlotte%20du%20val%20d'ognes%22&f=false|title=Aesthetics in Feminist Perspective|last=Lauter|first=Estella|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=1993|isbn=9780253114884|editor-last=Hein|editor-first=Hilde|location=Bloomington, Indiana|pages=23|chapter=Re-enfranchising Art: Feminist Interventions in the Theory of Art|ref=harv|editor-last2=Korsmeyer|editor-first2=Carolyn}}</ref>{{Sfn|Parker|Pollock|2013|p=106}}

After Sterling admitted the picture may not be David's, he called it a "merciless portrait of an intelligent, homely woman."{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} He also felt that the anatomy of the portrait was incorrect.{{Sfn|Mainz|2001|p=247}} Other critics suddenly found faults in the portrait, now that it was no longer considered a David and ascribed to Charpentier instead.<ref name=":0" />{{Sfn|James|1997|p=xiii}} [[James Laver]] wrote of the painting in 1964, "Although the painting is extremely attractive as a period piece, there are certain weaknesses of which a painter of David's calibre would not have been guilty."{{Sfn|Parker|Pollock|2013|p=106}}

In a more modern take, [[Germaine Greer]] wrote that the picture "does not seek to charm, nor does it seek to portray the sexual vitality of its sitter" and felt that it was a [[Feminism|feminist]] painting in nature.{{Sfn|Greer|2001|p=142}} Other feminist critics began to ascribe a [[Femininity|feminine]] aspect to the painting.{{Sfn|James|1997|p=xiv}}

The Louvre gallery discovered by Higonnet in 2014 was used by women to teach and be instructed in art.{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=58}} Higonnet therefore believes the painting is a portrait of a woman by a woman.{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=58}} The named woman, Charlotte du Val d'Ognes, once wanted to be a professional artist, but chose instead to give up art when she was married.{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=58}} Bridget Quinn describes the painting as a moment where "two young women longing to make art found themselves in a brief period of opportunity, when instruction, exhibition and even fame were possible."{{Sfn|Quinn|2017|p=59}}

